{"title":"Ambiguity-aware Truncated Flow Matching for Ambiguous Medical Image Segmentation","domain":"CV","seeds":[{"problem":"Ambiguous medical image segmentation requires predictions that are both accurate and diverse, but existing one-stage stochastic methods and vanilla truncated diffusion models entangle these objectives, so improving diversity typically hurts accuracy.","method":"Redefine inference with Data-Hierarchical Inference: marginalize stochasticity before the truncation point and supervise an explicit intermediate distribution at T_trunc (distribution-level objective for accuracy), then generate diverse samples after truncation at the sample level (diversity objective) via a diffusion/flow process. This two-stage, hierarchy-specific objective disentangles accuracy and diversity and enables simultaneous improvement with truncated, efficient inference."},{"problem":"In truncated diffusion models, the distribution at the truncation point is often approximated via adversarial sampling, which leads to low fidelity, inconsistent predictions, and missed low-frequency (rare but plausible) modes.","method":"Introduce Gaussian Truncation Representation (GTR): explicitly model the truncation distribution on the segmentation logit map at T_trunc as a multivariate Gaussian with learnable mean and covariance (low-rank + diagonal) predicted from image features (U-Net + 1×1 heads). Train this explicit prior by maximizing likelihood (Monte Carlo NLL) against ground truths, then freeze it for inference. This explicit parameterization preserves rare modes, improves consistency, and yields a reliable, high-fidelity truncation distribution."},{"problem":"After truncation, conventional diffusion lacks semantic guidance, yielding diverse but implausible or inaccurate masks; moreover, Gaussian constraints can disturb fine-grained segmentation.","method":"Propose Segmentation Flow Matching (SFM): use Flow Matching with an Optimal Transport schedule to transform from the GTR prior to target masks, and enforce semantic consistency at each timestep. Concretely, compute x_t = t·X1 + (1−t)·X_Ttrunc, predict the vector field g_θ(x_t), obtain x1_t = x_t + g_θ(x_t)·(1−t), and add a Dice-based loss against all available annotations per timestep to the FM loss. This semantic-aware flow yields diverse yet plausible segmentations and avoids Gaussian constraints intrinsic to DDPM-style sampling."}]}
